at|^*bAnalysis^*n      We can 'evaporate' a @h loser by deciding that the @h's must be 3-2.  The other @h loser goes away because we can finesse @hK (twice if we need to) so the @hK must be with East.      One of the @c losers can go on the @dQ, so the @d's need to be 4-3.   Given the @sQ lead the @sA is almost certainly with East, one could try the @sK anyway.   This does mean that we need West to have at least 3 spades, to stop West over ruffing East's third @s.   But if all this is true we can ruff the 3rd @s. Unblock @dAK.  Cross to @cA.  @dQ discarding low @c.  Finesse against @hK.  Cross to @cK.  Finesse against @hK.  Drop the @hK with our @hA and the final @h (trump) gives you 10 tricks.|
